which smart home systems to use. Here are my recommendations for three stage progresses setup depending on where you are currently in your smart home journey. For stage 1 is to go with something simple to start with. Option 1, Apple HomeKit. Option 2, Google Home. Option 3, Amazon Alexa. Move to stage 2. Be careful with Alexa. If you have an Alexa device like this in your home, you will be shocked by what I'm about to show you. Go to amazon.com and on your profile, select your account. In the next menu, find the option that says content and devices. Select devices and click on Echo Dot and then select the Echo Dot you own. There is a menu quite hidden over here under Privacy and Settings, so click on Alexa Privacy and in this menu, click on View Voice History. Here you will find all your recorded voice history, like this one for example. Everything you say is being recorded, but what is really alarming here is that Alexa records things even when you're not directly talking to Alexa. If you don't want this, click on Manager Alexa data and then choose how long to save or if you prefer, you can choose to delete your whole data history. Today I'm making my luxury apartment just a little bit smarter. I just received the Amazon Echo Show 15 and I already know that it's about to make my day-to-day life 10 times easier. Virtually everything in my apartment is managed by Alexa. Whether it's my music, schedule, grocery list, or even real-time updates on the weather and traffic. Oh, and most definitely my lighting setup in every room as well. By mounting the Echo Show 15 in the central location in my hallway, I'm not just enhancing my space, I'm creating a command center for myself and any of my guests that may be visiting me. For example, if you want to adjust the lights in my living room, it's done right from here. Gotta order some groceries for the play-offs this weekend. Easy, or maybe it's just time to unwind for the night. Alexa, it's time to relax.

I asked my mom if I could have a lady friend over today. She said okay, but only if she could stay in the room. Yeah, that wasn't gonna work for me. After a heated back and forth, we struck a deal. She'd lead the room, but only if she could set up the Arlo essential pantilindor camera to keep an eye on us. I told her Arlo is for protecting your home, not for spying on your dog's date, but a deal is a deal. Once the camera was set up and mom created a custom AI alert for any funny business, we texted Lola to kick things up. The date started off strong. We ran wild, burned off our energy, and then finally made our way to the couch for some snugs. But sure enough, mom caught the exact moment we got a little too close. We were busted in 2k, and you won't believe how she used the two-way audio. Hey, 2 feet apart, please. And she didn't stop there. She sent the incriminating footage to dad, but that backfired on her because he was far from upset. That's my boy. These are my top 5 smart home tech essentials to enhance your living experience. At number 1 is the Apple TV 4K, this is a great addition to the Apple ecosystem with built in Siri, HomeKit, Control and even FaceTime, and the operating system is miles ahead of any other smart TVs out there, most importantly it won't break the bank, they start from just Â£149 and are a great gift for anyone. Next up is lighting, this can really help enhance the mood of any living room space, and give in ambience for when you're either watching TV or just chilling with family. I'm using these Nano Leaf RGB light strips behind the TV and cabinet, and I think it gives a nice floating effect to the TV but also acts as a good lighting source for the room. I've also got these shapes from Nano Leaf which definitely give the place of character, and are a major talking point for my living room. These lights are also HomeKit enabled so you can control them from your Apple devices. Third is something that I think isn't prioritized enough, and that's the air quality in your home. I'll always recommend an air purifier, this is the never change 5 by shock, and I love it because the filter's last up to 5 years, and all you have to do is vacuum these trays every few weeks. It also has a percentage gauge on top to show you the air quality of your home. Now staying on the topic of cleaning a powerful vacuum that's easy to use and has some cool tech is the Dyson V15 detect. It comes with a soft brush head specifically made for hard floors which also has a built in laser to show you where the dirt is, but be careful because it can become addictive. For me though, it's now become a must have. Last but not least in order to control my smart home, some sort of smart speaker is needed. I'm using a few HomePod minis which I've dotted around the house, and this just makes it easier to control scenes and lights just using my voice. So those are my top 5 smart home tech products that I think would make your place just that much better.

Picture this, your entire neighborhood working together like a well-oiled machine. That's the future smart homes are bringing to our cities. We're talking energy grids that adapt to our needs, street lights that only shine when needed, and community-wide security that keeps everyone safer. But it's not just about convenience. These interconnected homes are reshaping how we plan our cities, making them more sustainable and efficient. Of course, it's not all smooth sailing. We've got two tackle issues like data privacy, and ensuring everyone has access to this tech. But the potential is huge. We could be looking at cities that are cleaner, safer, and just plain smarter.
